The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, Nov. 28: The government may soon decide on the successor of Sebi chief C.B. Bhave with a selection panel scheduled to hold final interviews on December 3. Among those shortlisted for the post, U.K. Sinha, chairman of the Association of Mutual Funds in India, and corporate affairs secretary R. Bandyopadhyay are said to be the top contenders, sources said.                            
	 New Delhi, Nov. 28: The government is planning to set up an authority to compensate duped investors by recouping money from fraudsters in the wake of various financial frauds. The disgorgement authority, which will be under the corporate affairs ministry, has been proposed in the aftermath of various stock market scams in which small investors lost crores of rupees.                            
	 New Delhi, Nov. 28: High inflation and input costs are inhibiting manufacturing growth. However, the performance of this segment, which contributes over 80 per cent to industrial output, improved in the first half of 2010 against the year-ago period, a CII-Ascon survey said.                             
	 New Delhi, Nov. 28: India has tightened norms for withdrawal of provident fund by overseas workers employed in the country, prohibiting them from taking back this money until they are 58 years old or are incapacitated.                             
	 Calcutta, Nov. 28: Coal India Ltd (CIL) has decided to close its loss-making underground mines to protect its bottomline. We are looking to close down underground mines which are loss making, CIL chairman Partha S. Bhattacharyya said.                            
	 Mumbai, Nov. 28: Driven by a strong domestic demand from automobile, infrastructure and other allied sectors, steel prices are likely to increase $25-30 (Rs 1,000-1,200) per tonne in the next three to four months, according to industry experts.                            
	 New Delhi, Nov. 28: The new premium of the Life Insurance Corporation has crossed Rs 50,000 crore during the April-October period this year, an increase of 66 per cent over the corresponding period last fiscal.                                                                                                                          
